>People remember Marble Blast as fondly as I do

>How to level design
When it comes to huge platforming levels, here's a fool-proof way:
>1. Finalize the damn movement equations
>2. Work with the slowest and shittiest character.
>3. Actually keep track of units. The marble blast series is a testament to level design and they literally used tiles to calculate and make the jumps satisfying.
>Measure the widest gaps the character can jump in tiles, the height of a jump in tiles, and maximum horizontal velocity in tiles per second
Finally
>4.Map out a level skeleton using tiles and unit cubes based on those calculations. If you have a feel for it,
>5. Design levels upward! The player will naturally want to get to the highest point in a map. Make the level revolve around a small number of sick jumps that require intermediate platforming to get to. People will see a balcony or overhang in the warehouse and immediately question how to ascend. They'll want to get to the roof
>6. Once the skeleton looks good, just replace a few of the previous obstacles with your assets, I guess. Sprinkle a few more in so it looks natural, but the path is clear
With close-quarters levels, like the warehouse, or levels with tight turns, you need to test with the fastest character as well to make sure it doesn't feel claustrophobic. I don’t care if the warehouse is comically large, if that's what it takes.
